text: A Lion King remake. My feelings are... mixed. On the one hand, it's almost symbolic since the Lion King is, to this day, an absolute stand-out in terms of animation quality, so using that as a stand-out for what CGI can do is appropriate. And James Earl Jones coming back is, honestly, awesome. And Lion King is still an absolute emblem of my Childhood. I don't think that much can ever change.  Buut‚Ä¶ then again... I'm not the biggest fan of Disney's live action (loosely in this case) reboots generally. And, of course, there's a certain... controversy... regarding this film, which after finding out about it has affected my view of the Film. So, I have very conflicting emotions regarding this. I want to be super excited, but the Controversy's holding me back.

text: You know, I am getting a little tired of seeing comments saying that this is Disney "not having any new ideas." The Jungle Book was, first of all, absolutely stunning to watch, Maleficent was NOTHING like Sleeping Beauty (very original in execution and story in comparison to the first), and each of the remakes they've done so far have had wonderful changes and additions to the stories that make them somehow even more enjoyable. They are telling the stories we love BETTER. Taking everything that we love about them and adding more wonderful and imaginative things. If you missed all of that, don't go bashing on _Disney_ for your inability to take in new information, or notice the vast changes that are right there to be seen.

text: To be honest, I mean the trailer is good (not as perfect as Godzilla: King of the Monsters). But at the same time, I won't be seeing it. I don't like how they're bring Lion King in Live Action, it just doesn't work for me. I guess (much like other remakes) it's because we want to see our favorite Disney characters. Lion King is without a doubt gonna be the worst Disney Remake ever. Aladdin was gonna be great, ehhh....until the actor for Aladdin showed up. And my god, he's so ugly.  You guys are asking me, what remake do I want to see that Disney should develop. Well obviously, I want to see Night on Bald Mountain in Live Action, in a PG-13 style. I always want to see my favorite Disney Villain break back into the main stream audience. Chernabog is the most important villain of the Disney Franchise, he's the reason why all your favorite Disney Villains gained power, or become evil (much like him). And if there's anyone who can play as him in CGI, it will have to be Andy Serkis. He's too perfect to be the actor in a CGI Chernabog. Aside from that, I also want to see Little Mermaid (Please cast Natalia Dyer for Ariel, because she looks and sounds a lot like her), and Snow White. They are great Disney classics, and they deserve remakes. Also, Maleficent 2 looks like a good idea. I actually get to meet Elle Fanning at London during my summer vacation. And she is really excited.  But sadly, this movie looks a little bit....bad. So, I'm just gonna save my money, and wait for Chernabog's film to be out soon. So, I think The Lion King remake will probably be the worst movie of 2019. Sorry......

text: I know the story is going to be great because I've seen the original, but um, I'll be honest, I don't like the presentation and the graphics. Benefit of hand drawn animation is easily recognizable and memorable characters that even kids with low cognitive development can relate, understand and enjoy. The dim lighting and complex hair animation over shadows some essential details. This movie seems like it's target audience is a bit mixed. Young children will enjoy it, but it might not be as memorable as the original. I guess teenagers and adults can revisit this movie with a new eye and enjoy the improved graphics? but I don't really feel the familiarity of the characters... Of course this comment is coming from an oldie who grew up in the hand-drawn animation era so it will be biased and I'm sure most people will enjoy the movie greatly.

text: Hmm, I guess we'll see how this goes.  I had no issues with Jungle Book, it offered a different adaptation, Beauty and the Beast however being practically a shot for shot remake felt weak, preying more heavily on nostalgia to get tickets sold. The Lion King? So far it looks like it'll be a shot for shot remake, but the lack of people, keeping this basically fully cgi may or may not work. I fear it will come off as a lesser version of the original albeit new and shiny and flashy and nostalgic and make a lot of money. I will reserve judgement until I see it, as I did with the other 2, and make my mind up then, but this is just my mind, anyone else can do as they please, they have their own brains.

text: Here's how I feel about the live action remakes: Pixar and Disney animation still exists and are making new and exciting projects (ex. Toy Story 4 and Gigantic) and these are more like filler in between them. Besides if all I had to watch was an okay Cinderella remake and a gorgeous update to the Jungle Book to get to Zootopia, I'll gladly take an interesting/fresh look at Dumbo, an Aladdin remake with Will Smith as the Genie (good cast choice), and a Lion King remake that still looks incredible and just fills my heart with joy if it leads to Gigantic and everything Disney and Pixar have coming up! Also these movies don't tarnish the originals, the originals still exist just go watch that instead! I'm excited for the new take on the Lion King. Donald Glover is an amazing choice and bringing back the iconic voice of Mufasa was a good call. While Scar feels irreplaceable, I have faith in Chiwetal Ejiofor as his voice better matches the feel this movie is going for, not to mention the fact that he's just an amazing actor who kills it! This movie has my money taken!

text: What bothers me about this movie is how absolutely unnecessary it is. I get that Disney wants to do live action remakes of all their movies. It's relatively easy since they are mostly copy and paste. However, what's the fucking point doing it with The Lion King? This is all CGI. There's not a damned thing live action about this at all. No humans. It's bullshit, this is an animated movie still. Just because it looks like real animals doesn't make any of this not animated. You might as well just watch the original film.  All these live action remakes are cash-grabby, but this is the most cash -grabby one there is. At least The Jungle Book had ONE human in it. THIS IS AN ANIMATED MOVIE!

But it still find for them to eat their own natural preys. => The best seducer rules. Be a seducer. Learn how to lick asses, suck dicks and eat vaginas.  ->There are races that are just evil. Hyenas. text: I haven't seen the Jungle Book but with the others in mind I'm still not sold on these live-action Disney remakes. Even the good ones make me go "OK but what was the point?". Lion King is also the weirdest choice to get this treatment. The point of the live action is to see real people do the stuff you've so far only seen animated characters do... This movie doesn't feature a single human though. Is it even fair to call this a live-action remake? It's CG animals on CG backdrops. It's more like re-animating if you will. It might be great. I'm just not really sold yet.

text: There's something about the CGI in this trailer that I just... really like. I don't know if I've ever felt this ok with this much CGI before. I think I'm really liking this.  Most movie CGI, at least when used for characters, makes me cringe and takes away alot of immersion for me.  As far as we've come with advancements in CGI, I'm still usually hesitant and disappointed with certain extreme efforts.. like Tarkin in Rouge One, for example. I can remember back around 10 years ago, I would hope against hope that surely, in 10 years time, CGI will have advanced so much that it will be at least borderline indistinguishable from reality... at least most of the time.  I've gotten used to being disappointed though. But... I got a feeling about this CGI.

text: *Young generation is in for a treat. This will make Frozen look like trash. Just PLEASE do not ruin this childhood classic, with SJW edits! Please!!!* The original is so pure in every sense. There is so much cultural significance in it, and it encapsulates so much.  Growing up. High hopes. The struggle for identity during young adult years. First love. Not giving up. Fighting for justice ect.  But overall I've got to say, my favourite is the European Pagan themes of Reincarnation, Rebirth via Reproduction, and Redemption run so deep. "He Lives in You", is an incredibly powerful song. Also, the way in which the European Writers so beautifully depict the spirit & nature of Africa, is phenomenal. There's a really deep respect there, and its art like this which inspires everyone, to have hope in an idea Greater, and to aim for something higher.  The original is, maybe not the most entertaining musical of all time, but EASILY the GOAT musical overall.   "Circle of Life", "We Are One", "Just Cant Wait To Be King!", "Be Prepared!", "He Lives in You", "Can You Feel The Love Tonight?"  *What other musical has this many ABSOLUTE CLASSICS?? Challengers welcome!!*

text: I'm not happy about this. There is no other reason to remake these iconic cartoon-movies, than to take our money. Just like in the 2nd half of the '90-s when they made sequels to these amazing stories (Aladdin, Lion King, Pocahontas etc.). Those sequels went straight to VHS or DVD, because they were nothing like the original. I have the same feeling about these new "live-action" (or rather: CGI) remakes. Disney, be creative again, find new stories, get some help from Marvel, Pixar, Star Wars (...maybe not from Star Wars)!

text: The Jungle Book, Aladdin, Cinderella, and Beauty and the Beast all have remakes already made or upcoming. But do they really have to make a live-action remake of the Lion King? I mean, I've heard that Beauty and the Beast is great, and I liked the Jungle Book movie, but I think that I've enough of these live-action remakes of classic Disney movies. My point is that it's annoying and tiring to be given the same stories just executed in a different way, I'd like new and original stories. If you like these remakes, don't take this as a personal attack on you, you can like whatever you wan't. I just felt I'd point out my opinion on the Disney live-action remakes. :)))))))

text: Idk how to feel about this. Some remakes of old movies are okay, but it takes away the originality of the first one. "The Lion King" (original) is a fantastic movie back then and still is a great animated movie. The animation on the original felt more appealing to younger and even older audiences. Mainly because of the impressive motions of the characters themselves that express who they are. Color scheme for many of the back rounds was really good as well. If this 3D version manages to surpass or be just as good as the original, then it's an alright movie. I just hope they don't fuck it up massively. After all, Disney is known for their amazing animation back in the 90s.

text: I remember the first Lion King movie so well. I was 6 years old and everybody at school was talking about it. My Dutch dad was kinda cheap and he knew someone who could give him an illegal copy, on VHS of course! That day he came home from work and proudly presented my brother and I the movie and we were beyond excited. But then my mom told him what I had done that day,...the boy next door and I had completely destroyed some isolation material at a nearby construction site by 'drawing' stick figures in it with nails and screws,...my dad was so angry he sent me to bed and he watched the Lion King that night with my mom and my brother. I was not allowed to see it.   Not gonna happen this time though! I'm gonna see this movie and no one is gonna stop me! :D

text: Yeees! Back in the day, The Lion King was a masterpiece in every aspect (story, music, visuals,). As far as this trailer shows, this movie wont excell , and wont bring anything new. For those saying CGI is the future, you have to remember that CGI doesnt age well,  5 years old CGI movie look crapish by now, while all of the 50+ year old classics remain top notch. In classic Animation everything depends on the hand, the hair, the lighting, the shades, full of love and soul, when a computer does half the job for you, you lost part of the magic and soul. Its like rewriting classic books, just to keep it, up to date. Feels unnatural. üòî  P. D. Whats next redoing episode 4,5,6 of Star Wars?üòÇ

text: Only folks who are 30 now can understand the level of emotion. I dont wanna isolate us but its the truth. It doesnt matter if you have watched the movie later on. If you were a kid and around 5 when the movie came out, remember the old trailer for the original with the whiskey voice narrator. then went to the movies and realized that love, hate, music, fun, jealousy, humbleness, humor and moral lessons all can come together in one movie. there is a reason why 80s or 90s love this movie often as the greatest disney movie of all time. it was our time. If you were 4,5,6 when those movies came out they were your introduction to theater, to visual entertainment, hell to disney and movies in general. I still remember the trailer in 94 and can compare it to this trailer 24 years later. its different if you watched lion king when it was released, in the cinema with your family and friends. this and aladdin will always hold the most special place to us. whoever is 30+, i know exactly what you felt when you watched this. no matter how good or bad the movie will be, the nostalgia will be worth it alone. enjoy your day fellows

text: Great, more childish, simplistic Disney garbage with a plotline about as dull, uninspired and predictable as the story of a five-year old who's just discovered 'goodies and baddies'. Related males (i.e. brothers) always form coalitions and would _never_ compete against one another- it would make absolutely zero sense from an evolutionary standpoint. text: I don't get behind those "It'll be horrible to see Mufasa die in HD" comments. I would be pretty impressed if the HD remake comes anywhere close to making that moment as impactful as the 2D animation. So far the character models I've seen aren't nearly expressive enough to show the terror in the the eyes of Mufasa or the selfsatisfied evil grin of Scar as you could see it in the 2D animation. You can't tell me that you could see any more than a hint of humanlike emotion on Raffiki's or Simba's face in this trailer. There's next to nothing, 'cause they're somawhat realistic looking animals. Real animals can't emote like humans can. I certainly hope the movie doesn't have the lack of expression this trailer does.

text: I hate to be a realist but I don't think this will work. All of these animals are computer generated as opposed to the original which were all hand drawn. Every emotion was painstakingly drawn in every frame, carefully capturing the humanity of each animal. That is what made the movie so great.  That doesn't happen in CGI. For example when Simba is lifted into the air you don't see the childish curiosity in his eyes like you did in the original. Computer graphics do a good job of capturing our reality but they fail to capture our humanity.

text: Okay I need to get my shit together. Was scrolling through facebook and came across the Australian lion king musical team, singing this song on an airplane. I started crying, cos you know. Feels. Then I went on youtube and searched ‚Äúaaaaah sibenya‚Äù (was to lazy to type full title of song, and I knew youtube would get the hint) and clicked the first one wich was a live performance by Lebo M. Cried again. Then I went through the comment section, and saw a comment wich asked ‚Äúwho‚Äôs here from the release of the trailer?‚Äù And I had to see the trailer again. For the third time within the last 15 minutes I started to cry again! This is so beautiful I have no words! I get thrown right back to my childhood home, where I‚Äôm sitting on the sofa fighting with my sister over the blanket we both want, while mom brings us homemade milkshakes, and tell us to valm tf down! This song gives me all this! And although I didn‚Äôt catch the beauty and worth in those moments back then, I see it so clearly now. Thank you Disney, for many beautiful, happy memories! You have, and will always be a part of my life! I will now take my own daughter to see this masterpiece once it premiers, and you can bet your ass I‚Äôm going to cry! ‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è
